WEBVTT

00:00.280 --> 00:01.640
We got one more kind of cool thing.

00:01.640 --> 00:03.400
This one luckily doesn't actually require,

00:03.400 --> 00:05.400
I don't think any code for you to write.

00:07.600 --> 00:09.560
I'm gonna talk about the React compiler,

00:09.560 --> 00:11.640
which I haven't really been able to talk about,

00:11.640 --> 00:13.940
but they've been talking about for a long time.

00:15.080 --> 00:17.880
So React compiler is basically going to be

00:17.880 --> 00:19.520
like free optimization for your code.

00:19.520 --> 00:21.480
So in theory, it should make your code

00:21.480 --> 00:25.280
either about the same to faster.

00:25.280 --> 00:27.880
So it should be no worse and it could be a lot faster.

00:28.720 --> 00:30.280
There are two hooks I didn't show you

00:30.280 --> 00:31.200
and I did that intentionally,

00:31.200 --> 00:33.740
one called use memo and use callback.

00:34.600 --> 00:36.800
This allows you to tell a component is like,

00:36.800 --> 00:38.360
you are too slow to render,

00:38.360 --> 00:40.960
please don't render unless I tell you to render.

00:43.400 --> 00:44.240
That seems like a good thing.

00:44.240 --> 00:46.680
It's like, why don't I tell that to all of my components

00:46.680 --> 00:49.200
that I know don't need to re-render themselves, right?

00:49.200 --> 00:53.840
What's a good example of like our header,

00:53.840 --> 00:54.880
no, it does change, right?

00:54.880 --> 00:56.600
Because of this, our cart.length.

00:57.480 --> 00:59.760
Pizza changes, model changes.

00:59.760 --> 01:01.080
We have some sort of dino-system

01:01.080 --> 01:02.840
in all of our components, don't we?

01:05.480 --> 01:07.880
Yeah, so we wouldn't really be able

01:07.880 --> 01:09.340
to do too, too much with it.

01:10.500 --> 01:15.500
But imagine you had a table that you rendered

01:18.640 --> 01:22.540
that had 5,000 things in it

01:22.540 --> 01:24.200
and you really didn't want it to re-render

01:24.200 --> 01:26.320
unless you like it had something to re-render.

01:26.320 --> 01:28.400
Like it's not cheap to re-render that component.

01:28.400 --> 01:30.860
You could use something called use memo to say,

01:30.860 --> 01:33.000
this component, please don't re-render it

01:33.000 --> 01:34.560
unless I tell you to.

01:34.560 --> 01:37.520
Use callback is another variation of that.

01:41.240 --> 01:43.960
So if you have performance problems,

01:43.960 --> 01:47.880
one, wait until you have a real performance problem first,

01:47.880 --> 01:51.120
then you can use use memo and use callback, right?

01:51.120 --> 01:52.920
That's my strong advice for you

01:52.920 --> 01:55.640
because once you introduce use memo and use callback,

01:55.640 --> 01:57.680
your code gets harder to like reason about

01:57.680 --> 02:00.280
because something will not update when you expect it to

02:00.280 --> 02:03.280
and you're like, why is this not updating, right?

02:03.280 --> 02:05.480
You'll change like some state or something like that

02:05.480 --> 02:07.040
and it won't update the view

02:07.040 --> 02:09.080
and you'll be like, why is this, right?

02:09.080 --> 02:10.040
This has happened to me,

02:10.040 --> 02:11.680
this is why I'm telling you about it.

02:11.680 --> 02:13.200
So please don't use it until you actually

02:13.200 --> 02:14.680
are solving a real problem

02:14.680 --> 02:16.840
because otherwise you're making your life harder

02:16.840 --> 02:17.680
for no reason.

02:19.080 --> 02:20.280
React is really fast.

02:20.280 --> 02:22.880
It's really good at making UIs

02:22.880 --> 02:25.040
and they're just making it faster all the time.

02:25.040 --> 02:27.360
So generally you can just trust it to be fast.

02:29.600 --> 02:32.480
Okay, so why are we talking about this now

02:32.480 --> 02:34.000
with React compiler?

02:34.000 --> 02:36.040
Well, React compiler is actually gonna go

02:36.040 --> 02:37.160
look at your code and say like,

02:37.160 --> 02:40.360
this thing can't change in these circumstances.

02:40.360 --> 02:44.000
So I am going to prematurely optimize this for them

02:44.000 --> 02:46.720
and then it'll just handle all that stuff for you.

02:46.720 --> 02:48.520
So it's gonna do some static analysis of your code

02:48.520 --> 02:51.160
is like this particular branch of code,

02:51.160 --> 02:52.400
this isn't gonna update,

02:52.400 --> 02:54.520
I'm just gonna say this never updates

02:54.520 --> 02:56.320
and then your code just gets faster.

02:56.320 --> 02:59.360
So it's using basically use memo and use callback,

02:59.360 --> 03:03.120
use memo particularly for you.

03:04.160 --> 03:05.400
So I'm very for this,

03:05.400 --> 03:07.000
like static analysis and all that kind of stuff

03:07.000 --> 03:08.800
and they're saying like this code branch can update,

03:08.800 --> 03:09.960
I think that's awesome.

03:10.960 --> 03:12.640
This used to be known as React forget.

03:12.640 --> 03:15.560
So if you ever hear React forget reference,

03:15.560 --> 03:16.720
they're talking about the React compiler.

03:16.720 --> 03:18.640
If for whatever reason it's trying to do something

03:18.640 --> 03:21.240
where you can do and you don't want it to,

03:21.240 --> 03:22.880
for whatever reason,

03:22.880 --> 03:24.040
you can go at the top of the page

03:24.040 --> 03:25.400
and you say use no memo

03:25.400 --> 03:28.200
and it will not ever optimize that.

03:28.200 --> 03:30.000
They request that if you have to do that

03:30.000 --> 03:32.400
to please tell them because they wanna know why.

03:33.360 --> 03:34.560
Because it shouldn't, right?

03:34.560 --> 03:35.480
You should never have to use that.

03:35.480 --> 03:37.320
They're saying that eventually they're going to eliminate

03:37.320 --> 03:39.200
all cases of when that should happen.

03:41.400 --> 03:42.880
So let's do something kind of fun.

03:42.880 --> 03:45.320
You can run this in your own codebases today.

03:45.320 --> 03:47.520
